  "prompt": "What is the technical stack of chat applications like WhatsApp, Facebook chat or Hangouts?",
  "response": "While I can't provide the exact current tech stack for these specific applications (as they may change over time), I can outline a typical modern chat application's technical stack:\n\nFrontend:\n- React Native (mobile)\n- Swift (iOS)\n- Kotlin/Java (Android)\n- React/Vue.js (Web)\n\nBackend:\n- Programming Languages:\n  - Erlang (WhatsApp)\n  - Java (Facebook)\n  - Go (Google)\n  - Node.js\n  - Python\n\nMessaging Protocol:\n- WebSocket\n- XMPP\n- Protocol Buffers\n- gRPC\n\nDatabase:\n- Cassandra\n- MongoDB\n- Redis\n- PostgreSQL\n\nReal-time Infrastructure:\n- Apache Kafka\n- RabbitMQ\n- WebRTC (for video/audio)\n\nCloud Infrastructure:\n- AWS\n- Google Cloud\n- Azure\n\nAdditional Technologies:\n- End-to-end encryption\n- Load balancers\n- Microservices architecture\n- Content Delivery Networks (CDNs)\n\nSpecific known details:\n- WhatsApp: Erlang/Elixir backend\n- Facebook Messenger: Java/Hadoop ecosystem\n- Hangouts: Previously XMPP, now proprietary protocols\n\nEach company has unique architectural choices based on their specific requirements.",
